Reasoning: The paper deals with the capacity of a communication channel, specifically the Carbon Copy onto Dirty Paper (CCDP) channel, which involves the transmission of information through a noisy channel with a known set of possible state sequences. This falls under the domain of information theory (cs.IT) and communication (cs.COMM). The paper also discusses the use of superposition coding and time-sharing, which are common techniques in signal processing (cs.SI) and multimedia (cs.MM). Additionally, the paper mentions the use of Gel'fand-Pinsker binning, which is a technique used in data storage (cs.DS).
